title: [d3-axis and d3-format] activate strictNullChecks and strictFunctionTypes
body:
In this PR, I activated strictFunctionTypes in d3-axis. To get it work I also needed to update d3-format.

In d3-format:
- Activate strictNullChecks in d3-format, just needed to change FormatSpecifier#precision.
- Use type `{ valueOf(): number; }` in `format` and `formatPrefix`.
- Function `format` can take a string, see [format-type-c-test.js](https://github.com/d3/d3-format/blob/master/test/format-type-c-test.js).
- Add `@throws` in JsDoc.

In d3-axis:
- Remove `"unified-signatures": false` from `tslint.json`.
- Use `$ExpectError` for failing tests.
- Activate strictFunctionTypes in d3-axis: change `Selection<SVGSVGElement | SVGGElement, any, any, any>` by `Selection<SVGSVGElement, any, any, any> | Selection<SVGGElement, any, any, any>`.

I add a test for `strictFunctionTypes`. Not sure if it is the best way to do it. Also CI build fail for them because some `$ExpectError` lines are not detected as failing. I'm wondering if `dtslint` test the code with [TS 2.7](https://github.com/Microsoft/definitelytyped-header-parser/blob/master/index.ts#L13) or not.

Finally, I don't think any new features from TS 2.3 may improve those definitions. So I kept the minimum version to 2.0.

If changing an existing definition:
- [x] Provide a URL to documentation or source code which provides context for the suggested changes: N/A. See tests.
- [ ] Increase the version number in the header if appropriate.
- [ ] If you are making substantial changes, consider adding a `tslint.json` containing `{ "extends": "dtslint/dt.json" }`.

This change is a small usability improvement, rather than a change to improve correctness.

Calling `R.prop("propName")` returns a function whose return type is generic, as the current typings indicate. However, sometimes you know upfront that the resulting function will always be called with an object where `"propName"` holds a specific type. A good example is with `R.compose/R.pipe`. Consider this snippet from the tests:

```ts
R.pipe(R.prop("indent"), indentN)
```

`indentN` takes a number, so the code will only work if the function returned by `R.prop` is always called with a `Record<"indent", number>`.

With the current typings, this cannot be specified, so the user has to write:

```ts
R.pipe<Record<"indent", number>, number, (s: string) => string>(R.prop("indent"), indentN)
```

to get a proper type inferred for the function returned by `R.pipe`.

With this change, the user can indicate that the "indent" prop must hold a number, such that just writing the following results in the correct type being inferred for the `R.pipe` result:

```ts
R.pipe(R.prop<"indent", number>("indent"), indentN)
```

The new signature is added below the existing ones (and has an extra type parameter), so this doesn't change the behavior of existing code at all. It just makes this usability win opt-in.

title: Select2 split v4 and v3
body:
Select2 v4 has several backward incompatibilities with v3: some properties have had their name or type changed, others have been added or deleted, all events have been renamed, etc. The Select2 definition file started as a definition for v3 and was changed little by little into v4. So that now, the definition has mixed typing from v3 and v4. This PR solves this issue, dividing the definition into two: one for each version. 

The following steps have been taken (see commits):
1. Deleting some redundant events methods appearing twice.
2. Coping the contents of the select2 directory into select2/v3 without changing any files.
3. In the v3 directory, changing `tsconfig.json`, removing v4-related types and bring back those from the old v3. Therefore, I used the `index.d.ts` git history and I checked also [Select2 3.5.3 Documentation](http://select2.github.io/select2/).
4. Deleting the remaining v3 types in the v4 file, especially the event names.
5. Linting v4 according to `dtslint` recommendations.
